Boxplot (seaborn)¶

Out[25]:
<AxesSubplot: xlabel='price_per_m2'>

The Boxplot visualises the distribution of the house and appartement prices per m2. It's visible, that most of the listings are within a very small range at the lower end of the spectrum. The below table further shows this through the amount of listings in the price per m2 categories which correlate to the boxplot.

Low: 0-5'000 CHF per m2

Medium: 5'000-8'000 per m2

High: 8'000-12'000 per m2

Very High: 12'000 - 100'000 per m2

Quantile-Quantile (QQ-) plot¶

In [20]:
# Variable (standardized)
x = 'area'
df_qq = df_apartments_database
df_qq['var'] = (df_apartments_database[x]-df_apartments_database[x].mean()) / df_apartments_database[x].std()
print(df_qq.sort_values('var')[['area', 'var']])
    
# Plot
sm.qqplot(df_qq['var'], line ='45')

Barchart (matplotlib)¶

In [21]:
# Group data by rooms (only the topmost 15 values are shown)
df_bar = df_apartments_database['rooms'].value_counts().nlargest(15).sort_values(ascending=True)

# Values for barchart
napart = list(df_bar.values)
index = list(df_bar.index.values)
y_pos = np.arange(len(index))

# Figure
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7,4))
ax.barh(y_pos, napart, align='center', color='lightblue', alpha=0.9)
ax.set_yticks(y_pos, labels=index)
ax.set_xlabel('Number of apartments', fontsize=10)
ax.set_ylabel('Rooms', fontsize=10)

# Show graph
plt.show()

Piechart (matplotlib)¶

In [22]:
# Group data by rooms (only the 8 most frequently occurencies by rooms)
df_bar = df_apartments_database.rooms.value_counts().nlargest(8).sort_values(ascending=True)

# Simple bar chart
sizes = list(df_bar.values)
labels = list(df_bar.index.values)
explode = (0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0.1) # increases distance of pieces

fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(5,5))
ax1.pie(sizes, 
        labels=labels, 
        explode=explode,
        autopct='%1.1f%%',
        shadow=False, 
        startangle=90)
ax1.axis('equal')  # ensures that pie is drawn as a circle.

plt.show()

Scatterplot (matplotlib) with regression line¶

In [24]:
# Subset
df_sub = df_apartments_database.loc[(df_apartments_database.price >= 1000)]
print(df_sub.shape)

# Scatterplot
plt.figure(figsize=(7,4))
plt.plot(df_sub.area, 
         df_sub.price, 
         'o', 
         markersize=3.5,
         color="lightblue")

# Regression line (b = slope, a=intercept)
b, a = np.polyfit(df_sub.area, df_sub.price, 1)
print(b)
print(a)

# Plot regression line
plt.plot(df_sub.area, 
         b*df_sub.area + a, 
         linewidth=1,
         linestyle='dashed',
         color='darkred')

# Add title and axes labels
plt.title('Scatterplot with regression line', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('price', fontsize=12)
plt.xlabel('area', fontsize=12)

# Set fontsize of tick labels
plt.xticks(fontsize = 10)
plt.yticks(fontsize = 10)

plt.show()
